  "signature": "ed25519:25f0547d87ece1a7e215f6de4096dd5f6a9b3589309c4dd9f8b3fb14d998d9e50a20d1bb5b4845322a1c6074d63156d5dcb1525170f30cd8d7e8f0bb12abbe0c",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is a commercially validated finite element solver with documented V&V test suite per ISO 9001 quality management. DePuy Synthes internal FEA tool version 4.2 has been verified against Ansys for all relevant element types (SOLID186, CONTA174). FDA in-house Python post-processing scripts are version-controlled in Git with unit tests covering all QoI extraction functions. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2 for medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/code-verification-level2",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and manufactured-solution benchmarks confirm correct implementation of large-deformation elastoplastic formulation. Cantilever beam benchmark with known analytical solution reproduced to within 0.3% for linear regime. Contact formulation verified against Hertz contact solution for cylindrical-on-flat geometry representative of screw-block interface. All benchmarks documented in verification report VR-2023-04."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/discretization-level2",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation performed on three systematically refined meshes (coarse: 48k elements, medium: 192k elements, fine: 768k elements). Grid convergence index (GCI) for stiffness QoI = 0.8%; for yield force QoI = 1.1%; for force-at-40mm QoI = 0.6%. All GCI values well below the 5% threshold. Production mesh uses medium refinement (192k elements) providing adequate accuracy with acceptable computational cost. Achieved level 3 due to systematic three-level convergence study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/solver-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver with automatic time-stepping; convergence tolerance set to 0.1% force residual norm. All production runs achieve convergence within tolerance; no diverged load steps. Energy balance checked at each increment; energy error < 0.05% for all cases. Iterative linear solver (PCG with incomplete Cholesky preconditioner) residual < 1e-8 for all increments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/use-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Standard operating procedure (SOP-FEA-001 Rev C) governs model setup, boundary condition application, material assignment, and post-processing for ASTM F1717 simulations. Independent peer review of model setup performed by a second analyst not involved in original model construction. Checklist-based review covers 47 items including unit consistency, constraint application, and output extraction. No use errors identified in peer review; minor documentation clarification implemented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-form-level3",
      "rationale": "Continuum elastoplastic model with isotropic hardening (Chaboche parameters calibrated from tensile coupon data for Ti-6Al-4V ELI per ASTM E8). Contact modelled with augmented Lagrangian formulation; friction coefficient μ=0.2 based on tribological literature for titanium-on-UHMWPE. Geometric nonlinearity (large deformation) activated. Model form choices are consistent with the physics of the ASTM F1717 test and with published FEA literature for spinal implant constructs. Sensitivity analysis confirms that ±20% variation in friction coefficient produces <2% change in all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-inputs-level3",
      "rationale": "Geometry derived from calibrated CMM measurements of production screws (n=5 screws measured; mean dimensions used; dimensional variability propagated as input uncertainty). Ti-6Al-4V material properties from lot-specific tensile coupon testing (n=6 coupons per lot; E = 114 ± 3 GPa, σ_y = 880 ± 18 MPa). UHMWPE block properties from supplier data sheet with ±10% uncertainty on elastic modulus. All input uncertainties propagated through Monte Carlo sampling (n=500 runs) to compute model parameter contribution to uval. Input uncertainty contribution to total uval < 40% for all three QoIs, confirming model form dominates."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-samples-level2",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested: n=6 at Laboratory 1 (FDA CDRH) and n=5 at Laboratory 2 (DePuy Synthes). All specimens from the same production lot, traceable to material certificates. Screws assembled to UHMWPE blocks per ASTM F1717 protocol. Dimensional inspection of all test specimens confirms compliance with operating envelope bounds (diameter 7.48–7.53 mm). Inter-laboratory variability assessed; coefficient of variation for stiffness across labs = 3.1%, confirming reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-conditions-level2",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under ambient laboratory conditions (22 ± 2°C, no fluid immersion) per ASTM F1717. The standard does not require physiological temperature or wet conditions for this test type. However, all validation testing was conducted at a single nominal loading rate (5 mm/min) with only sparse coverage at 1 mm/min (n=2) and 25 mm/min (n=1). This sparse multi-rate coverage results in achieved level 1, below the required level 2. This shortfall is acknowledged and documented; the operating envelope upper bound on loading rate (25 mm/min) is set at the maximum tested value to prevent extrapolation. The decision team accepted this shortfall given that rate effects in quasi-static titanium testing are well-characterized in literature and the sparse data at rate extremes remain within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/input-equivalency-level2",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs mapped directly to experimental measurements for each of the N=11 specimens: actual measured screw dimensions used per specimen rather than nominal values. Material properties assigned from the same production lot as test specimens. Boundary conditions replicate ASTM F1717 fixture geometry as confirmed by fixture dimensional drawings. No significant uncontrolled parameters identified between simulation and experiment. Equivalency mapping table documented in technical report TR-2024-08, Table 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/output-comparison-level3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed for all three QoIs using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval. Acceptance threshold E/uval < 1.96 (95% confidence interval). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.71, yield force E/uval = 0.83, force-at-40mm E/uval = 0.44. All three QoIs pass acceptance criteria with margin. Individual specimen comparisons also performed; no specimen shows QoI difference exceeding 9.1% (below 10% threshold). Force-displacement curves compared graphically for all 11 specimens; FEA ensemble envelope encompasses experimental scatter across full displacement range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/qoi-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary metrics specified in ASTM F1717 for characterizing spinal implant mechanical performance and are directly linked to the regulatory decision (510(k) substantial equivalence). Stiffness characterizes functional performance under physiological loading; yield force characterizes safety margin against permanent deformation; force at 40 mm characterizes ultimate structural integrity. All three are directly extractable from both FEA output and experimental load-displacement data without intermediate transformation. Relevance traceability documented in QoI justification memo QJ-2023-11."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/validation-relevance-level3",
      "rationale": "Validation activity is a direct replication of the COU: the same FEA model, the same screw design, the same test standard (ASTM F1717), the same QoIs, and the same acceptance bounds are used in both validation and the regulatory submission context. The operating envelope declared in the COU was defined to match the validated parameter space, ensuring no extrapolation in the intended use. The validation activities were designed prospectively with pre-registered acceptance criteria (registered in FDA CDRH internal tracking system prior to data collection), eliminating post-hoc adjustment of thresholds. Relevance assessment documented in validation plan VP-2023-07, Section 4.2."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2024",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors for COU1 (non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending prediction). Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved level 1 vs. required level 2) arises from sparse multi-rate coverage and is mitigated by: (1) restriction of the operating envelope upper bound on loading rate to the maximum tested value (25 mm/min); (2) consistency of sparse multi-rate results with acceptance bounds; and (3) published literature supporting quasi-static rate insensitivity of Ti-6Al-4V in this regime. All three QoIs pass the pre-registered acceptance criterion E/uval < 1.96 with substantial margin (maximum E/uval = 0.83). The operating envelope is explicitly bounded with concrete parameter limits, and an applicability constraint restricts use to non-cannulated designs. Coverage gaps at envelope extremes are honestly documented and do not invalidate the assessment given the conservative bound-setting approach. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through uncertainty quantification to validation metrics is complete and traceable. The decision team accepts the model as credible for its intended use within the declared operating envelope and applicability constraints.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
